1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,930
Shortly after World War II, Seedy got a job with the Customs Division of the U.S. Post Office Department.
2
00:00:07,120 --> 00:00:12,769
He liked his work, but after five years he became dissatisfied with the confinement,
3
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:19,730
regular hours, low pay, and the seniority system with its relatively narrow chances for advancement.
4
00:00:20,160 --> 00:00:22,050
Then he got an idea.
5
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:26,850
He had learned a great deal about what it takes to be a successful importer.
6
00:00:27,040 --> 00:00:33,090
Why not set himself up in the business of importing low-cost gift items and toys?
7
00:00:33,440 --> 00:00:40,210
C.D. knew many successful importers who didn't have his knowledge of the ins and outs of this business.
8
00:00:41,120 --> 00:00:46,850
It's been ten years now since C.D. decided he wanted to go into business for himself.
9
00:00:47,040 --> 00:00:50,690
But today, he's still working for the customs office.
10
00:00:50,960 --> 00:00:51,730
Why?
11
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:56,850
Well, every time C.D. was just about ready to cut loose on his own,
12
00:00:57,040 --> 00:01:00,050
something happened that stopped him from taking action.
13
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:07,570
Lack of money, economic recession, new baby, need for temporary security, trade restrictions,
14
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:12,930
and more excuses all served as reasons for waiting, for postponing.
15
00:01:13,680 --> 00:01:18,690
The real truth is that C.D. let himself develop into a passivationist.
16
00:01:18,960 --> 00:01:22,610
He wanted conditions to be perfect before he took action.
17
00:01:22,720 --> 00:01:27,009
Since conditions were never perfect, C.D. never took action.
18
00:01:28,320 --> 00:01:36,289
Here are two things to do to help you avoid the costly mistake of waiting until conditions are perfect before you act.
